The internal justice of the case, with regard to the state for which the privateer acts, is satisfied if the conti-act be an equal one: that is, if the expense and danger be equal in value to the chance of prizes. For if this chance is much more. valuable, the surplus ought to be given to the stat-2¹3 as if any one had beforehand purchased a haul of fish at an unusually low price.

IV. But even if justice strictly speaking be not violated, there may be an offense against the loving our neighbour, especially in a Christian view: as if it appear that such privateering will not burt the general body of the enemy, or their king, or the guilty portion of them, but the innocent3 and will inflict upon them calamities which it would be cruel to inflict, even on those who are personally indebted to us. And if, besides this, such a privateering warfare is not likely to conduce, either to the termination of the war, or to any notable damage of the enemy's public power, then it must be considered un- worthy a right-minded man, and especially a Christian, to make a gain in this way out of the unhappiness of the times.
